" = [ \\\"gtk\\\" ];\\n    };\\n  };\\n};\\n```\\n\\n#### 3. Address Conflicts (Hyprland / Desktop Specifics)\\nIf you are using **Hyprland** or another Wayland compositor, note that `xdg-desktop-portal-hyprland` does **not** provide a file chooser[9][11]. You must have `xdg-desktop-portal-gtk` installed alongside it to \\\"fill the gaps\\\"[9][12].\\n\\nIf you recently updated your system, ensure that your `portalPackage` or `extraPortals` are not being overridden by conflicting configurations (e.g., both NixOS and Home Manager defining the same portal settings)[5][8]. Home Manager settings often take precedence over NixOS system settings[8].\\n\\n#### 4. Clear Cached Portal Configurations\\nSometimes, corrupted cache files in your home directory prevent the portal from starting[2]. You can try clearing them:\\n```bash\\nrm -rf ~/.config/xdg-desktop-portal/\\n```\\nThen, restart your session or the portal service:\\n```bash\\nsystemctl --user restart xdg-desktop-portal\\n```\\n\\n#### 5. Environment Variables\\nIf the portal is running but applications still fail, they might be missing the environment variables required to \\\"see\\\" the portal[13]. Ensure your environment is set to use the portal:\\n```nix\\nenvironment.variables = {\\n  GTK_USE_PORTAL = \\\"1\\\";\\n};\\n```\\n*Note: In some modern environments, this is handled automatically, but explicitly setting it can help debug applications that are not properly sandboxed or configured.*\\n\\n### Still failing?\\nIf you continue to see errors like `No such interface` or `startup job failed`, check your logs immediately after trying to open a file:\\n```bash\\njournalctl --user -u xdg-desktop-portal -f\\n```\\nThis will show you exactly which component is rejecting the request (e.g., a timeout or a missing D-Bus interface)[4][6].\\n\\nSources:\\n[1] [github.com](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGahROfk7RUXRWCqIxnG3zGiMIitzvVoatIet9cjjvxQzNllrH2EsNmTyINw85wPgznHPuWDjZru7CXW